showed.text: Definition 3 A set of vertices $X \subseteq V(G)$ is a twin-cover of $G$ if for every edge $e = ab \in E(G)$ either 1. $a \in X$ or $b \in X$, or 2. $a$ and $b$ are true twins. We then say that $G$ has twin-cover $k$ if the size of a minimum twin-cover of $G$ is $k$.

Let $\mathcal H_k$ be the class of graphs of twin-cover $k$. Then $\mathcal H_k \subseteq \mathcal{TM}_{2^k+k}(2)$ and a tree-model of any $G \in \mathcal H_k$ may be constructed in single-exponential FPT time.

showed.text: Definition 3.1. $X \subseteq V(G)$ is a twin-cover of $G$ if for every edge $e=\{a,b\} \in E(G)$ either 1. $a \in X$ or $b \in X$, or 2. $a$ and $b$ are twins, i.e. all other vertices are either adjacent to both $a$ and $b$ or none. We then say that $G$ has twin-cover number $k$ if $k$ is the minimum possible size of a twin-cover of $G$.

Definition 3.2. $X \subseteq V(G)$ is a twin-cover of $G$ if there exists a subgraph $G'$ of $G$ such that 1. $X \subseteq V(G')$ and $X$ is a vertex cover of $G'$. 2. $G$ can be obtained by iteratively adding twins to non-cover vertices in $G'$.
We note that complete graphs indeed have a twin-cover of zero.
The vertex cover of graphs of bounded twin-cover may be arbitrarily large.

displayed_definition: In graph $G$, twin-cover number is the minimum number $k$ such that there exists a set $M$ of size $k$ such that $G-M$ is a union of cliques where each pair of vertices from the same clique are true siblings in $G$.
